Some Observations Worth Noting

If score is not given, then that particular entry is completely useless. We can't substitute it with zero, because that would be doing injustice to the product, and some genuine reviews. On top of that the actual review written in words might be completley speaking otherwise. There are other methods which can be used, like analyzing the words used and the user profile to understand if the rating is missing because of some data entry problem or is it some kind of incomplete or fake review that is unsuitable for analysis. But, here we don't have access to NLP kind of analysis, hence we don't opt for it.

If author field is not given, it might be irrelevant for a few types of recommendation systems, but for something like apriori or user-user collaborative recommendations it becomes important to identify. Moreoever it becomes really important to understand if the missing entry of the "author" is repeated elsewhere. If it is supposedly repeated, meaning that user has bought multiple items and hence, that would cause loss of valuable information regarding the user behaviour.

If extract is not given, then that particular entry might be useless if we are going to any kind of recommendation system other than that of popular recommendation settings. So, we have to take a decision to drop these appropriate entries when we are going for content based recommendation systems.

There are some expected types of entries into the particular column like for example, "source" is expected to be purely a string, but there might be some other entries other than alphabets and some serious characters. We can eliminate them. Country is strictly a string value, but we should check the same, and so that can be used to correct some entries with approximate entries with most matching ones.

We can create new columns out of old ones, like date here, which will help us in further analysis.

Two entries, Source and the website corresponding to that source both are redundant, hence we can simply drop the source column and retain domain column.

6412 rows × 11 columns

There seems to be two kinds of duplicate entries here, one in which it might mean that review given on one domain might be different than another. Here we are blindly assuming that user doesn't have the same username across the domains, hence two users with same name but different domains will be treated as different users, even though the extract is exactly the same and product is also exactly the same.

The other review is the same user, same domain same product but either different rating or different extract. In that case, we have to consider the most recent extract and most recent rating. If there is a collision in terms of date, we have to consider the lowest rating (if there is a rating difference) or choose extract with most number of words (assuming that the user didn't write crappy reviews and the extract actually describes in detail the working of the project.)

Proposition for Data Cleaning¶

Step 1. Drop any entries within the rows where the product under review is not mentioned. No matter what the URL is, which can change all the time, the product have to be there for us to take any decision. So, we will try to extract information about the missing product name from the URL. (there seems to be only one such entry here so no problems regarding that).

Step 2. Convert the datetime kind of format and check it out. If there are any exceptions while conversions they can be appropriately handled.

Step 3. Eliminate Duplicate entries by taking taking author names and trying to find out if they belong to the same domain, if so if they wrote multiple reviews for the same product. If so, check which review is the latest and take that review as the honest one and drop the other. If there is a date conflict, go for the rating, and choose the lowest rating. If the rating is in conflict too, then go for highest number of words in the extract column and choose for that particular entry and drop the others. We are going to exclusively deal with index vlaues here, so we have to be careful.

These are the top phones that have got the maximum rating. But, that alone is not the criteria for phone recommendations here. For being a top recommendation being popular, it should have two characteristics :

  1. Be top rated most of the times i.e. mean rating for the phone should be highest of all.

  2. It should be highest occurring of all i.e. it should be extremely frequent within the count.

Please Note :

Here two phones with similar features but a little different variations (e.g. different color), are considered as different products. In other words, it is assumed that those variations (colors) within the features are assumed to be totally different features in themselves. It requires huge amount of processing power and also some deep analytics of NLP to deal with similarity between two different phone version. We will try to attempt them but for now, we will consider those products are different products.

Noting from the above the indices of the particular phones whose indices and the particular ratings are given. Now, let us create another column where the mean score for that product is attributed. But before that we have to group the phones by their type.

In [56]:
data_stage3_product_grouping=data_stage3.groupby("product") # We will come back to these again in a new form later on.

It is to be noted that phones that are sold should be sold by a minimum amount of the total phones sold to be even eligible for consideration of the top recommendations. Hence, we will eliminate all the phones that are sold just one or two in quantity and consider the ratings for the most sold phones and then sort those phones in accordance to their mean rating.

I have set here threshold to be 10% of the most sold phone's frequency (the total sales to be cut off and hence has been noted down.) from the very strong assumption that most frequently occurring product is the product that is most sold, which might be extremely wrong assumption.( I myself haven't rated a lot of items I bought).

In [57]:
threshold_phones=value_count_products[0]/10 # This threshold value can be changed.
ratings_phones={}
######################################################################
for each_phone in value_count_products.keys():
    #print(each_phone)
    if value_count_products[each_phone]<threshold_phones:
        #print(value_count_products[each_phone])
        #print(each_phone)
        continue
    else:
        #print(each_phone)
        #print(data_stage3_product_grouping.get_group(each_phone)["score"].mean())
        ratings_phones.update({each_phone: data_stage3_product_grouping.get_group(each_phone)["score"].mean()})
####################################################################
In [58]:
 # Sorting the values so that recommendations come up automatically.
####################################################################
# Function that sorts the dictionary based on the values
####################################################################
def sort_dict_values(given_dict,reverse=True):
    sorted_values=sorted(given_dict.values(),reverse=reverse)
    sorted_ratings={}
    for i in sorted_values:
        for k in given_dict.keys():
            if given_dict[k] == i:
                sorted_ratings[k]=given_dict[k]
                break
    return sorted_ratings
###############################################################
# End of funtion
###############################################################
sorted_ratings_phones = sort_dict_values(ratings_phones)

The above cell is copied from the internet at address given below : https://stackabuse.com/how-to-sort-dictionary-by-value-in-python/

In [59]:
###########################################################################
# Gives top phones based on the recommendations and the threshold as set before.
###########################################################################
def give_top_phones(sorted_ratings_phones,how_many_phones=10,min_rating=None):
    phones=[]
    if min_rating!=None:
        for each_item in sorted_ratings_phones:
            if sorted_ratings_phones[each_item]>=min_rating:
                phones.append([each_item,sorted_ratings_phones[each_item]])
        #print(phones)
        phones=pd.DataFrame(phones,columns=["Product","Avg_Rating"])
    else:
        phones=pd.DataFrame(phones,columns=["Product","Avg_Rating"])
    return phones[:how_many_phones]#pd.DataFrame(phones,columns=["Phone","Rating"])
###########################################################################
# End of function
###########################################################################

A product should be mentioned atleast 50 times for it to be eligible to be separated according to the given question. From those ones, the things that are to be rated atleast 50 times should be separated out. We have already eliminated entries where the ratings not given entries are dropped. So, first let us create the index of items which have been mentioned at least 50 times.

In [78]:
data_stage5_org=data_stage3.copy()
In [79]:
data_stage5=data_stage3.groupby("product") # Frist grouping by product, and eliminating those that aren't mentioned 50 times
In [80]:
#this produces indices for the entries where the corresponding product has atleast 50 ratings, after we have taken that 
#there are atleast 50 entries for a given product.
k=[] # Contains the products which have mentions atleast 50 times, and the places where they are mentioned.
#########################################################################
for each in data_stage5.indices:
    #print(len(data_stage5.indices[each]))
    if len(data_stage5.indices[each])>50:
        #print("Yes Entered")
        k.append(list(data_stage5.indices[each]))
#########################################################################

##########################################################################
l=[]
for i in range(1,len(k)):
    r=k[i]
    for each in r:
        l.append(each)        
#########################################################################

Observations There is an interesting pattern here where most of the entries are from the more recent times. It is undertandable because of growth and popularity of domain diversity and online sales. It is to be noted that there are a lot of repurcussions on this. The most serious one being that the maximum number of products any single person can buy and rate will fall down drastically because of this higher concentration of distribution along one particular side implying that there might be a lot of fake entries into this. This needs to be further studied and explored, as we do later and might serve as a strong reason to favour a few decisions that are revealed later on.

We are now going to check if there are duplicated entries for the same author, same product. If they are then we check for the date and take the latest ones, and drop the older ones. Because the latest entry can be considered as the most valued entry and the previous ones can be abandoned. Below cells demonstrate how it is checked. We go ahead with a function to do the same for all the authors and products.

step by step approach :

  1. First identify the duplicate entries in author and product column together, indicating that entries are most likely updates.
  2. Check if the particular user has most recent entry for the same product. Take that most recent entry as the genuine entry of that particular user.
  3. Check if their extract is the same or changed, if the score is same or changed (over time). If score changed to something or extract changed to something that is not valid, go back with the valid entries.
  4. Make a list of all duplicate entries, and assert that all the entries need to be dropped. Then search for a reason and mechanism for each type of entry not to be dropped. If they are found to be valid and not to be dropped, then modify the entry, or do some kind of modifications in the original dataframe and then later drop them from the list of entries that are to be dropped.
  5. Finally create a matrix of ratings and users, and then let the models and algorithms work on it.

In [98]:

#Now, if we take an approximate, we can get an idea of how many reviews a user has posted on an average for each different product.
print("The Average Number of reviews per Author",len(data_stage7["product"].unique())/len(data_stage7["author"].unique()))

The Number of Unique Products 3517
The Number of Unique Authors 231
The Number of Unique Extracts 81211
The Average Number of reviews per Author 15.225108225108226

This is by no means clear or definitive of anything, but it is indicative that a user on an average has bought 15 products (neglecting a lot of other considerations). But, if we take the total amount of entries in the entire dataframe we have around 85 thousand entries. That obviously means that not just that users have not just rated the product, but they have rated it multiple times and a lot of times have updated their rating. We have already seen that the maximum number of ratings given by an author is misleading and if we ignore that too, the maximum occurrence is around 40,789, which is obviously riddiculous number for any given user to rate or write a review about. It is clear hence, that there are multiple ratings for the same product by users, and also there are generic users who haven't given their author name. What a waste !

Considering, the number of unique extracts some of them by the same user and some by different users, some by the users who declined to give their author name, some by the same user rating the same product at a later time i.e. editing their product review. This is just never ending saga and it is suggestive that a proper username should be made must for any reviewer in future to make our model work good.

Very important Conclusion Note here that, since we have got that at an average a user buys 15 products. In that line of thought, it is highly likely that the product is never bought more than once. If such is the case then the number of counts of each product shouldn't be more than the total number of customers. That means no product should be counted more than the total number of authors viz. 231. But, that seems to be not the case seriously. That means the products were rated multiple times and most probably at different times.

Now that we get a complete feel for the data that is present, we will go for a function that will help us create some analysis. This is a just a synthesis of all the steps we have taken before coming to this point.

In [103]:
##########################################################################################
# This function eliminates the older entries for same users same product but different times. But it should have a datetime column.
###########################################################################################

def update_user_entries(dataframe_given,columns_of_interest=["author","product"]):
    #Making a list of duplicated entries of same author, same product
    temp_index=dataframe_given[dataframe_given.duplicated(subset=columns_of_interest,keep=False)]
    indices_to_drop=list(temp_index.index)
    temp4=temp_index.groupby(columns_of_interest[0])
    for each in temp4.indices.keys():
        #print(temp_index.index.is_unique)
        #print(each)
        temp2 = temp4.get_group(each)
        temp5 = temp2.groupby(columns_of_interest[1])
        #print(temp2,temp5.indices)
        for each_product in temp2["product"].unique():
            #print(each_product)
            temp3 = temp5.get_group(each_product)
            #print(temp3)
            to_not_drop_index=temp3.date.sort_values(ascending=False).index[0]
            #print(to_not_drop_index)
            indices_to_drop.remove(to_not_drop_index)
    return list(set(indices_to_drop))
##########################################################################################
#
###########################################################################################

In [108]:
data_stage7_temp=data_stage7.loc[to_drop_entries_cols] # Creating a temporary frame based on this

If we carefully observe these particular entries, we see that sometimes the extract is same, but sometimes it is different. We will haven't decided on what to do with the identical entries for the author columns that we have, So we will decide that here, and perhaps try to eliminate or modify those entries for author column adding some random suffixes to it whenever we find different extracts for two different authors and two different dates or times.

Our earlier functions gave us one list (to_drop_entries_cols) that has entries that repeated in some way or the other and the other list that contains the entire original entries as specified (i.e. more than 50 times product mentioned and more than 50 review users).

Strategy

Convert the users whoever are there and cap it off at 50. Let me explain : suppose if we have a particular user within these entries where the users have hundreds of entries like that of "Cliente Amazon" or "Amazon Customer"; for our practical purposes we will divide those particular entries, pick random 50 and give it a modified name like "Amazon customer 1" and "Amazon Customer2" etc. and change that for every 50 entries. So, 50 entries will be the maximum any generic user is going to get. This way, we can't loose information for our machine learning model. We will suppose that we have generated random user out of the confused and collaborated lot that we got here.

My Presumption is that those particular users like the ones mentioned before, are generic entries and the users declined to put up their name. But, their reviews are valuable nevertheless. Hence, we can perhaps make synthetic groups of fixed size out of them, based on the associative Rule Learning, and comeup with various baskets, which can be used to generate synthetic authors of that particular product basket.

Observations : There seems to be same review for different phones (or perhaps the same phones registered as different phones in the product category) that needs proper checking. It is a gross negligence in trying to properly not club the two different products as the same. It is extremely difficult to now identify similarity between products and club them together. Perhaps we can check the cosine similarity matrix and club products of the same type together. We will deal with it later.

Now, within this dataframe, we can see that there are duplicate entries. Hence, what we will do is group them by score, choose the latest one. If there is a conflict on the latest one, then we will choose the lowest score one.

We should now convert the above entire thing into a function, in a step by step so that we can make a proper function.

In [118]:
##########################################################################################
#Function that does extract real duplicates from a dataframe with proper consideration and also latest entries taken. It assumes date column is present along with extract columns.
###########################################################################################
def extract_real_duplicates(dataframe_given,columns_of_interest=["author","product"]):
    data_stage7_temp=dataframe_given
    kill=data_stage7_temp[data_stage7_temp[columns_of_interest[1]].duplicated(keep=False)].groupby(columns_of_interest[0])
    dropping_temp=[]
    #############################################################################
    for each_author in kill.indices.keys():
        kill2=kill.get_group(each_author)
        kill3=kill2[kill2["extract"].duplicated(keep=False)==True] # Here we have to consider all the duplicates to make an informed decision of which one to keep.
        kill4=kill3[kill3[columns_of_interest[1]].duplicated(keep=False)].groupby(columns_of_interest[1])
        #############################################################
        for each_product in kill4.indices.keys():
            #print(each_product)
            terr=list(kill4.get_group(each_product).index)
            #print(terr)
            item=kill4.get_group(each_product).date.sort_values(ascending=False).index[0]
            #print(item)
            terr.remove(item)
            dropping_temp=dropping_temp+terr
        ##############################################################
    #############################################################################
    return dropping_temp
##########################################################################################
#
###########################################################################################   
temp_check=extract_real_duplicates(data_stage7_temp)

63254 rows × 8 columns

These are the entries that need definite dropping from our original dataframe. That is when we will be in peace for further analysis. But before that we will try to figure out a mechanism in which we distinguish between two generic users of a particular domain. Remember we have already eliminated users who have accidentally put up the same extract as a double entry, or have updated their review is already taken care of.

To the Evaluator

Due to a lot of personal reasons, and complications in connection with time availability, the idea to attempt to classify users into classes based on the baskets of things created due to association learning and then renaming idea of generic users is abandoned. Instead, I will attempt to just pick some random samples from the generic users to some random groups and group them into corresponding customer classes (class of customers refused to specify their name). To do that I do some exploration and set out the right number of authors' classes based on some categories.

Notes :

So, there are a total of 6255 days of data has elapsed. That is around 17 years of time. So, in the time, from my own estimates and common sense, even we are need to think that even if we buy one cell phone every 3 months (which is highly unlikely in itself first) that would still lead to 51 phones in 17 years of time. Hence, it is really good, if we can cap it off to 50. So, we will generate random numbers and club them into one class of amazon customer. We will do it until we have users such that each will have not more than 50 for general customers. Those general users will be as follows. "Amazon Customer" upto "unknown" which is first 11 of the authors.

In [129]:
author_indices={}
###################################################################################
for each in temp:
    to_send=[]
    kill=data_stage7_temp[data_stage7_temp["author"]==each].index
    upto=int(len(kill)/50)
    indices_to_consider=np.random.choice(kill,size=(upto,50),replace=False)
    for each_array in indices_to_consider:
        to_send.append(each_array)     
    kill=np.setdiff1d(kill,indices_to_consider)
    to_send.append(kill)
    author_indices.update({each:to_send})
    
    #if len(kill)!=0:
       # print(kill)
##################################################################################

This new list (author_indices) contains all the splitting that we need to do for the given author name modification.

It is worth noting here that there are some language differences. Despite that, it looks like the user might have rated a few phones better than the ones he already has, and perhaps potentially buy them given the opportunity. The best example is to observe that "Lenovo Motorola Moto G Smartphone" is mentioned as top recommendation, even with slight modification and is also the product that was rated by the user. That means, the user most likely didn't get to lay hands on the phones that are top recommendation, like Huawei P9 Lite, which is very much a slight modification of the phone that is already listed as bought by the user. That literally means that there is improvement in the possibilities for the corresponding domain to make it available to the particular kind of users, to better sell it. We can go further and check the dates and everything else so that we can make some informed decisions on what tends to be the right time and right way to launch a product so that a particular class of users buy the product.

In [145]:
# Copied this function without any change from the project files. Hence not putting any decoration to it.

def get_top_n(predictions, n=10):
    # First map the predictions to each user.
    from collections import defaultdict
    top_n = defaultdict(list)
    for uid, iid, true_r, est, _ in predictions: #uid and iid stand for userid and itemid.
        top_n[uid].append((iid, est))

    # Then sort the predictions for each user and retrieve the k highest ones.
    for uid, user_ratings in top_n.items():
        user_ratings.sort(key=lambda x: x[1], reverse=True)
        top_n[uid] = user_ratings[:n]

    return top_n

KNN with Means for Item-Item Collaboration¶

In [148]:
from surprise import KNNWithMeans
from surprise import accuracy
###################################################################
algo_KNN_itemitem = KNNWithMeans(k=50, sim_options={'name': 'pearson_baseline', 'user_based': False})
algo_KNN_itemitem.fit(trainset) # We are using the same train set as before.
##################################################################

KNN with Means for User-User Collaboration¶

from surprise import KNNWithMeans
from surprise import accuracy
####################################################################################
algo_KNN_useruser = KNNWithMeans(k=50, sim_options={'name': 'pearson_baseline', 'user_based': True})
algo_KNN_useruser.fit(trainset) # We are using the same train set as before, once again.
#####################################################################################
test_pred_useruser = algo_KNN_useruser.test(testset)

Some Notes and Final Answers for the Questions Raised in the Problem Statement.¶

The first five questions are correspondingly answered through the project, hence they needn't be mentioned here again.

7.Findings and Inferences I tried to scatter them through out the project, but to cut short in breif, there seem to be a specific set of features that grow out and stand out exponentially. It can be properly exposed if we take time to study how the distribution of date and time corresponds with the type of features and the types of phones that are sold.

There is also a crucial feature missing i.e. the features of the phone are to be listed in a separate file/column more legibly and the year of manufacturing has to be specifically mentioned. There is a possibility that older models might be selling more than newest models, and that is completley lost. We can't just judge the model launch year by the first appeareance year. It leads to complications. Hence, it is suggested to discretize the features more importantly, and rank the important features (like battery capacity, screen size etc.) from less important features (like color, back panel).

We need a more in-depth model that bags the words mentioned in features to declare and decide the importance of that particular feature, and decide by it.

Most of the data points are skewed in frequency towards more recent years indicating a number of things. But the most important thing is the popularity of the features. Since it is skewed, features get more diverse, uniform, and lot of options will be available. That might lead to more sales as already noted. But, if the sales are to increase, we need to have proper recommendation to proper user. Information is the key to the user. Here, most of the times user information is missing and we had to classify the generic users, not according to initial plan but randomly (due to lack of time). This can be improved.

9.check for Outliers The outliers can only be possible in numerical columns and there is no more than one numerical column, in the sampled data set considered here and the maximum score is same all across, so we didn't even need the normalization. But otherwise, we can have this method added later on.

11.Usage of Popularity Based Recommendation:

This is usually required when we have zero user data i.e. user is not logged into or haven't purchased any particular product yet with the particular domain. Popularity based recommendations work really well the user is very specific regarding the product he wants i.e. the criteria (not to be confused with the product itself or its features). In the pricing arena usually popularity based recommendations work out like charm, because most popular ones are the most sold ones and user always wants things that are price friendly.

12. Usage of Collaborative Filtering Methods : This is usually used when users are a lot more specific on what they want. Usually when a user searches for something instead of just browsing, it means he/she is looking for a specific product. The product might not match description, which might disappoint the user. In that case, we should come up with the closest match to the search of those who have made similar searches and those who have bought similar items. Both, item-item and user-user collaboartion is of vital importance in displaying relevant results. These should be used in business solutions where there is a necessity for a product, but needn't be exact match, and also user information and prior history is available for that particular interaction.

13. Further methods to improve Recommendations : If a few issues raised through out this project are addressed we can improve upon already existing methods to improve recommendations. Apart from that we can perhaps dig a bit more into associative rule mining from apriori. We can create bundles like necessities and associates kit, a bag of some kind of offer a discount. Check out how many within that baggage are taken together and how many are selected. That way we can always improve our recommendations.

Proper user information, especially age, sex, location is the very important criteria for better recommendation because tastes vary according to these significantly. For e.g. showing a coffee grinding machine to a location where coffee beans are not readily available, even though it is most popular, will be completely useless, it only leaves the customer with negative feedback.

Another method of recommendation to check for the gap in the date of purchase and date of review and the date of score. That will leave with a lot of possibility that the user has written review of a product after extensive thoughts and hence any wording made is not of initial euphoria but the well thought out product review. Those words are extremely valuable. If we could devise a method from NLP such that we can separate the extracts containing feelings, experiences with a product from the actual descriptions, problems and working principles of a product, then it would be an excellent guide to perfect and proper recommendation of a quality and relevant product. I think for the same search we can give identical products of the same specs. Hence, the recommendation system, if it can, take extra effort to separate Quality products and grade them, it would be a solid system.
